C.  Manuscript and/or Economics Editor (international, intermittent, 2 person-months)  

5.  The manuscript and economics editor shall be responsible for the manuscript editing of 
the Key Indicators for Asia and the Pacific1 special chapter and assist in preparing the highlights, 
including the tables and charts included in the publication. He or she will also assist with 
preparing the highlights and the presentation materials for the launch of the Key Indicators. 

6.  The editing will include two rounds of review of the typeset version. The editor will also 
make  suggestions  as  to  the  layout.  Particularly  for  the  special  chapter  and  highlights,  the 
manuscript and economics editor will 
(i)  reorganize text so that the subject matter is easy to understand and is logically 
presented; 
(ii)  eliminate wordiness and repetition, and reduce ambiguity; 
(iii)  query discrepancies, possible typographical errors, and non-English terms; 
(iv)  edit tables and figures, and recast if required; 
(v)  identify  obvious  errors,  including  mathematical  calculations,  and  point  out 
questionable proper names, bibliographic references, and the like, but excluding 
fact checking; 
(vi)  ensure that the text conforms to the ADB Handbook of Style and Usage; 
(vii)  ensure that subheadings are consistent and logical; 
(viii)  check references to tables, figures, appendixes, and parts of the text; 
(ix)  edit notes to ensure that the text reference is correct; 
(x)  edit reference lists; 
(xi)  check the author's final changes in close coordination with the author;  
(xii)  check and sign off on the layout; and  
(xiii)  perform other tasks as may be assigned. 

7.  The output is a manuscript-edited special chapter, highlights, Framework of Inclusive 
Growth Indicators (FIGI), and presentation materials. 

D.    Economics and Statistics Specialists (10 national consultants, 60 person-months) 

8.  The specialists should have a background in economics and/or statistics and experience 
in working with official statistics (statistics produced by governments). They should also have 
advanced  knowledge  of  Microsoft  Excel  and  automated  business  processes.  They  must 
exercise due diligence in undertaking processes concerning data compilation and validation. 
Moreover,  they  should  have  good  writing  skills.  In  particular,  the  specialists  will  assist 
Development Indicators and Policy Research Division (ERDI) staff to 
(i)  compile  and  validate  statistics  from  assigned  regional  members  and  other 
sources; 
(ii)  using applications of the Statistical Database System, generate, review, and 
finalize assigned statistical tables under the guidance of ERDI international staff 
and the Key Indicators coordinator; 
(iii)  study  the  assigned  theme  and,  together  with  their  ERDI  staff  counterpart, 
analyze the available data and other information; 
(iv)  review and update the statistical definitions and concepts that are utilized in the 
preparation of Key Indicators; 
(v)  write a report on the analysis of the assigned theme; 

1  Key Indicators refers to Key Indicators 2013, Key Indicators 2014, or both.
